Many of you have questions about what's happening on campus today. Here are some answers:

We assume power will be restored Friday. If that happens, classes and normal operations will resume. We will not make that decision until power is actually restored. For the latest, sign up at http://warnme.berkeley.edu and follow
Some buildings are running on limited emergency power, which could fail if overloaded. There is not sufficient backup energy to handle normal operations on campus.

The power is off. Students, staff and faculty should stay away from campus. Latest information: http://news.berkeley.edu Updates on : -> Residence halls, dining commons: https://sa.berkeley.edu/October-2019-PGE-power-outage -> Research labs: https://vcresearch.berkeley.edu/campus-power-outage-closure-october-9-2019 -> AirBears: https://technology.berkeley.edu/pge-outage/faqs

In some cases, buildings may appear to be partially energized from temporary battery backup, backup generators, and in some cases, power diverted fr/ our small cogeneration power facility. There will not be sufficient backup power to handle normal operations or classes.
Employees are encouraged to stay home unless they are critical employees. The campus is not closed, but services are limited. Many residence halls may be without power.

"May the education you have received here serve not just your lives but your society well. May your years ahead be richly rewarding and fulfilling, and may you enjoy much happiness." - Chancellor Carol Christ #CalGrad

"...a Berkeley degree is also a privilege, and with it comes the responsibility of using your education to contribute to a society that needs your energy, your intelligence, and your help." - Chancellor Carol Christ #CalGrad

"Finally, I hope you take from Berkeley a sense of public responsibility. I am immensely proud and grateful for the hard work and sacrifices that you, and your families, have made to bring you to this moment." - Chancellor Carol Christ #CalGrad

"I hope you will take with you the capacity for moral reasoning, the ethical judgment that you will need to exercise in many areas of your life. Let it become your lodestar as you navigate a tumultuous time." - Chancellor Carol Christ #CalGrad

"I hope you will take with you a sense of confidence in your own abilities and powers. In whatever sphere you choose to live and work, you have much to contribute. Belief in yourself is the foundation of leadership.” - Chancellor Carol Christ #CalGrad

“I hope you will take the ability to voice what it is you believe, even when you know others may not share your perspective. Do this without wedding disagreement to disrespect, on your own part or that of others.” - Chancellor Carol Christ #CalGrad
“I hope you will take the capacity for empathy, for understanding perspectives different from your own, which Berkeley has tried to instill in you.” - Chancellor Carol Christ #CalGrad
“Complex and thorny issues are not solved by dictate, they reach conclusions through the willing engagement of a diverse, thoughtful, and open-minded community.” - Chancellor Carol Christ #CalGrad

“As surely as this institution has left its mark you, you have left your mark on Berkeley. When you saw the need for change at our institution, you seized it – and our university is richer and better for your efforts.” - Chancellor Carol Christ #CalGrad
“Your Berkeley – the years that you have been on campus – has been marked by momentous change in the world.” - Chancellor Carol Christ #CalGrad
